item.title: China Orders U.S. to Close Consulate in Retaliatory Move
item.description: The U.S. and China each moved rapidly Friday toward closing one of the other’s diplomatic facilities and evicting diplomats, an unprecedented step in the midst of heightened tensions that was followed by calls to return to more normal relations.

item.title: Goldman Settles 1MDB Dispute With Malaysia for $3.9 Billion
item.description: The Wall Street bank will pay $2.5 billion to the government of Malaysia for its role in the alleged theft of billions of dollars from a government investment fund, and guarantee the recovery of $1.4 billion in assets allegedly stolen from the fund.

item.title: Spain Increases Restrictions as Coronavirus Cases Rise
item.description: Public authorities in Spain announced new anti-contagion measures as the number of coronavirus cases continued to rise, dimming hopes for economic revival.

item.title: Hagia Sophia, a Shifting Symbol in Turkey, Once Again Opens Up to Islamic Prayers
item.description: President Recep Tayyip Erdogan attended Muslim prayers in the Hagia Sophia two weeks after he declared the building—a museum for the past 86 years—a mosque again in a controversial move aimed at reviving nationalist sentiment.

item.title: Economic Recoveries in U.S., Europe Take Diverging Paths
item.description: The U.S. economy lagged in July and Europe’s bounced back, according to fresh surveys of purchasing managers, evidence that the two economic powerhouses are recovering at different speeds from the coronavirus pandemic.

item.title: Russia Cuts Interest Rates to Record Low
item.description: The central bank cut its key interest rate as the pandemic pushed the economy into a deep recession and forced President Vladimir Putin this week to delay a flagship $360 billion national development plan by six years.
